’s central Luangwa Valley is the homeland of the Valley Bisa whose cultural practices have enriched this environment for centuries. Beginning with the intrusions of warlords and later British colonials, successive generations have experienced the callousness and challenges of colonialism. Their homeland, a slender corridor surrounded by three national parks and an escarpment, is a microcosm of the political, economic and cultural battlefields surrounding most African protected areas today. The story of the Valley Bisa diverges from the myths that conservationists, administrators, and philanthropists, tell about Africa’s environmental and wildlife crises.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aBisa (Zambian people)xHunting. 0aSubsistence huntingzLuangwa River Valley (Zambia and Mozambique) 0aSubsistence huntingzLuangwa River Valley (Zambia and Mozambique). 0aWildlife conservationxSocial aspectszLuangwa River Valley (Zambia and Mozambique) 0aWildlife conservationxSocial aspectszLuangwa River Valley (Zambia and Mozambique). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aafricas environmental and wildlife crises.  aanthropologists.  acallousness and challenges of colonialism.  aconservationists.  aenriched environment for centuries.  ahomeland of valley bisa.  aintrusion of warlords and british colonials.  amost african protected areas.  astory of valley bisa.  athree national parks and escarpment.  azambia.  azambias central luangwa valley.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311099822140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781785331589?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781785331589423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781785331589/original  a978-3-11-099822-1  Berghahn Books Com